<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Henry, Alexander. Travels in the Red River Department (Abridged), 1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0024</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">54</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">on at the foot upon a slow trot.  At some distance we saw abundance of Buffaloes and Roes browsing unmolested.  After Satisfying our curiosity we descended and joined our party.  About noon we received orders to halt and prepare for our arrival at the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">schian's</span> camp which was close by.  This ceremony required some time and the chiefs made several turns through the camp on horseback advising the Young men to dress in their best manner so as to look like brave warriors such as was expected of them<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Each now outvied the other in order to render their looks savage and ferocious &#8212; So that the whole in a short time appeared completely hideous<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Even their horses were daubed over with white and red earth to correspond with their riders and add fright to their already frightful appearance.  When all were ready We mounted and proceeded in the nicest order, Singing, admiring one another and appearing as proud and stiff as possible from the influence of their dress<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We now crossed a small rivulet, the banks of which were ornamented with a few stunted willows and was the only wood we had seen</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">since</p>

